1. What is a Linked List?
Imagine a treasure hunt — each clue doesn't give you all the answers. It gives you the next clue's location. That's a linked list.
A linked list is a chain of nodes where each node holds:

Data — the actual value (like 10, 20, 30…)
Next — the address of the next node

Unlike an array, nodes are not stored side-by-side in memory. Each node can be anywhere — it just points to the next one.
____________________________________________________________________________________________________________
2. Key Terms
TermMeaningNodeOne box — holds data + next pointerHeadThe first node (entry point of the list)TailThe last node (its next = null)nullMeans "nothing after this" — end of list
____________________________________________________________________________________________________________
3. Node Structure in Java
javaclass Node {
    int data;      // the value stored
    Node next;     // pointer to next node

    Node(int data) {
        this.data = data;
        this.next = null;  // by default, points to nothing
    }
}
________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

4. Types of Linked Lists
a) Singly Linked List

Each node points to the next only. One direction — forward only.

10 → 20 → 30 → null
b) Doubly Linked List

Each node has TWO pointers — one to next, one to previous.

null ← 10 ⇄ 20 ⇄ 30 → null
c) Circular Linked List

The last node points BACK to the first node. No null — it loops.

10 → 20 → 30 → (back to 10)
____________________________________________________________________________________________________________
5. Basic Operations
a) Create a list
javaNode head = new Node(10);
head.next = new Node(20);
head.next.next = new Node(30);
// Result: 10 → 20 → 30 → null
b) Traverse (print all nodes)
javavoid printList(Node head) {
    Node temp = head;           // start from head
    while (temp != null) {      // keep going till end
        System.out.print(temp.data + " → ");
        temp = temp.next;       // move to next node
    }
    System.out.println("null");
}
c) Insert at Beginning
javaNode insertAtStart(Node head, int val) {
    Node newNode = new Node(val);
    newNode.next = head;   // new node points to old head
    head = newNode;        // new node becomes new head
    return head;
}
d) Insert at End
javaNode insertAtEnd(Node head, int val) {
    Node newNode = new Node(val);
    if (head == null) return newNode;  // list was empty
    Node temp = head;
    while (temp.next != null) {        // go to last node
        temp = temp.next;
    }
    temp.next = newNode;               // attach new node
    return head;
}
e) Delete a node by value
javaNode deleteNode(Node head, int val) {
    if (head == null) return null;
    if (head.data == val) return head.next;  // delete head
    Node temp = head;
    while (temp.next != null) {
        if (temp.next.data == val) {
            temp.next = temp.next.next;  // skip the node
            break;
        }
        temp = temp.next;
    }
    return head;
}
____________________________________________________________________________________________________________

6. Linked List vs Array
ArrayLinked ListMemoryContiguous (side by side)Scattered (anywhere)AccessO(1) — direct by indexO(n) — must traverseInsert at startO(n) — shift everythingO(1) — just change headInsert at endO(1) if space availableO(n) — traverse to endSizeFixed (mostly)Dynamic (grows freely)
Simple rule: Arrays are fast to read, Linked Lists are fast to insert/delete.
____________________________________________________________________________________________________________

7. Time Complexity Summary
OperationTimeTraversalO(n)Insert at headO(1)Insert at tailO(n)Delete at headO(1)Delete middle/tailO(n)SearchO(n)
____________________________________________________________________________________________________________

8. Common Interview Questions (remember these!)

Reverse a linked list
Detect a cycle in a linked list (Floyd's algorithm)
Find the middle of a linked list
Merge two sorted linked lists
Remove nth node from end
Check if linked list is a palindrome
____________________________________________________________________________________________________________
9. One Analogy to Remember Everything
Think of a train. Each coach is a node. Each coach has passengers (data) and a connector to the next coach (next pointer). The engine is the HEAD. The last coach's connector is open (null). You can add a new coach at the front or back — but to reach coach 7, you must walk through coaches 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 first.
